snippet.textDisplay: After watching Neil's videos when they came out I also came to the conclusion that one of the few use cases for the Mac Pro is upgrading from a janky trash can setup (when every expansion card needs an adapter every setup with it is probably just a mess) and streamlining your production environment after using Macs for a long time. Being used to OSX and the available (audio) tools makes it hard to switch, so the Mac Pro is kind of the best of both worlds. You simply pay a premium for using OSX in a PC form factor. If you earn good money with the work you're doing on your Mac, this premium doesn't really matter anyways, ROI might be higher but not having to change your workflow and probably improving reliability can compensate for that. But if your already on windows or linux or have no benefit from OSX, its still a bad value proposition. It's two main benefits over normal servers or workstations is low noise and OSX. If you don't care about noise (or have a dedicated server room) and need a high performance density it even loses that.

snippet.textDisplay:
Not only Audio professionals can get a grater use out of a rack mounted MAC. In the film industry it has been standard to have a Mac Pro Trashcan, or Mac Mini with Expension Card mounted in a Server Rack next to Card Readers, a Storage Server and some monitoring and grading gear.
DIT cards such as these had hundreds of cables running around and it's annoying to use. Having most of the important gear enclosed in one Unit that wasn't constantly overheating when capturing 4 or more video streams will be awesome in so many situations.
I can also see this beeing used for mobile editing suits where u need a lot of power in an easy to transport case. I worked at a company where we used to transport arround iMacs in huge Pelican cases with Thunderbolt to fibre network cards and loads of peripherals, which where around 45kg each. With this u can have one case for the mac and a case with a monitor which are both smaller and lighter to carry around.
I love the flexability of this thing and I have quite a few more usecases for this thing in my head, where this makes way more sense than the normal version.

Fun Fact: at my old job we also used to cut the top and bottom stand/handle things of the old cheese grater mac pro off, to make our own rack mount version of it :D
